The OSSL_PARAM_utf8_ptr() is a macro, not a function.

The code you need to write with the macro is:
char *foo;
OSSL_PARAM_utf8_ptr(foo);

And the macro will modify the value of foo. That is, the pointer will change.

Normally when a value can be modified, you need pass a pointer to that variable, so:
char *foo;
OSSL_PARAM_utf8_ptr(&foo);

But because OSSL_PARAM_utf8_ptr() is a macro, it can modify the variable without having to take a pointer.

